Date: Tue 5 Apr 2016
Source: Washington Daily News [edited]
http://www.thewashingtondailynews.com/2016/04/05/unknown-disease-damaging-wheat-crops/


Unknown disease damaging wheat crops
------------------------------------
A disease not yet identified has affected wheat crops in Beaufort County [North Carolina, NC], due to excessive rain and overall wet field conditions. Though farmers and agriculture officials originally believed the problem to be _Soil-borne wheat mosaic virus_, they have since found that not to be the case. Affected wheat samples have been sent for diagnosis at NC State University. It is unknown how the disease will affect yields and profits from this year's [2016] wheat crop.

_Soil-borne wheat mosaic virus_, a virus that was previously believed to be a problem across many areas of the state, not only has been ruled out in Beaufort County, but other damage previously believed to have been [caused] by the virus, has proved to be attributed to other diseases and problems.

"It's a matter of importance, but not everybody is being affected by this," said Rod Gurganus, Beaufort County Cooperative Extension. "We were thinking we were on to something affecting wheat across the state, but we've found there are different diseases happening in other areas. This problem is not the same as in other areas."

The disease is reducing the number of tillers, which can potentially have a huge effect on yield. "(The disease) is basically causing the wheat to be stunted and some of the growth to die," Gurganus said. Crops across Beaufort County have been negatively affected by an excess amount of rain and a lack of cold weather. "A lot of crops were standing in water, and that's when the problems started showing up. It's not everywhere, but on certain farms, it's widespread. It's bad [but] at this point, there's nothing that can be done."

[Byline: Jonathan Rowe]

