Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[A large number of diseases due to fungi and other pathogens can affect wheat. The wet conditions described above would favour many of them and also increase the risk of simultaneous infections by multiple pathogens, which can lead to severe yield losses. In addition, the humidity would also increase the risk of wheat stored after harvest to be affected by pathogens and pests adding to yield losses and decreasing the grain quality.

_Soil-borne wheat mosaic virus_ (SBWMV; type species of genus _Furovirus_) was first described from the USA in the 1920s. It occurs in various parts of the world and can also affect triticale. SBWMV causes one of the few diseases of winter wheat that can destroy an entire crop of a susceptible cultivar. Yield loss depends on virus strain, crop variety and environmental conditions. Symptoms vary and may include mild green to prominent yellow leaf mottling, rosetting, and moderate to severe stunting of plants. SBWMV is transmitted by the soil-inhabiting fungus _Polymyxa graminis_. The virus can survive for several years in soil and dry crop residues, protected by the fungus. It is spread with contaminated soil, by water and mechanical means, but is not seed-transmitted. Disease management relies mainly on use of resistant crop cultivars.

The report above illustrates the importance of molecular diagnosis for plant diseases, since similar symptoms can be due to different pathogens as well as effects of external factors on the host. Symptom expression may also be influenced by, for example, host and/or pathogen strains and environmental conditions.

